did.abstract: Theodore Payne was a horticulturalist, nurseryman, and expert on California native plants. Materials in the Theodore Payne papers include personal and business records, records pertaining to his professional interests and activities, photographic material, publications on horticulture and gardening, landscaping records, Payne's writings and speeches, herbarium specimens, and artifacts.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Collections are processed to a variety of levels depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived user interest and research value, availability of staff and resources, and competing priorities. Library Special Collections provides a standard level of preservation and access for all collections and, when time and resources permit, conducts more intensive processing. These materials have been arranged and described according to national and local standards and best practices.

Prior to accession at UCLA Library Special Collections, this collection was arranged several times, and the original order of the papers was not maintained. In 2016, it was reprocessed by Amelia Parks, LA as Subject Visiting Archivist at the Theodore Payne Foundation. During this reprocessing project, Amelia Parks arranged and described the materials to the subseries level. Additionally, preservation photocopying on materials with water damage and mold was undertaken, and the damaged originals were not retained due to their poor condition. Some ledger covers have been removed due to their degradation or high acidity. Where appropriate, the ledger covers were photocopied and placed with contents.

Revisions to the description, physical arrangement, and post-processing activities were undertaken by Kathryn Brunet, Collection Management student assistant under the supervision of Jasmine Jones, in 2019.
Materials that were previously housed in a box 26 were rehoused, and there is no longer a box 26 in the collection.

We are committed to providing ethical, inclusive, and anti-racist description of the materials we steward, and to remediating existing description of our materials that contains language that may be offensive or cause harm. We invite you to submit feedback about how our collections are described, and how they could be described more accurately, by filling out the form located on our website: Report Potentially Offensive Description in Library Special Collections.

bioghist.head: Biographical History
bioghist.p: Theodore Payne (1872-1963) was a horticulturalist, nurseryman, and expert on California native plants. He was born in 1872 in Church Brampton, Northamptonshire, England. He moved to California in 1893 and owned and operated a nursery in Los Angeles from 1903 through 1960.

Theodore Payne's education started at Ackworth Academy, a Quaker boarding school in West York, England. In 1888 Theodore Payne apprenticed with J. Cheal & Sons for training in the nursery and seed business. John Cheal was a horticulturist, offering a full line of services, and Payne spent time in each of the departments, learning all elements of the nursery business.

In 1893, Payne began working as head gardener at the ranch of Madame Helena Modjeska, a stage actress located in Santiago Canyon, Orange County. In 1896 Theodore Payne moved to Los Angeles and obtained a position at Germain Fruit and Seed Company as a flower seedsman. Before opening his own nursery, Payne traveled to England and Europe, including Germany and France. On his travels he made contacts with several nurseries and maintained many of those relationships throughout his career. In 1903, Theodore Payne purchased Evans nursery at 440 South Broadway, Los Angeles. The Payne Nursery offered a variety of plants, seeds, and bulbs, as well as landscaping services. Two years later the Payne Nursery moved the office to 345 South Main Street and stayed there until 1931 when he moved his nursery to Los Feliz Blvd. In 1907 Payne married Alice Noyes, and they remained married for 56 years, until Theodore Payne's death.

Throughout his career as a nurseryman, Payne kept active with community outreach and education. He taught horticulture and gardening in many schools around the Los Angeles area and planted educational gardens on school grounds. He was also an active member of many committees and clubs, among them the Southern California Academy of Sciences and the board for Rancho Santa Ana Botanic Garden. Payne was also contracted on many jobs for state and federal projects, and acted as an advisor for maintaining California's native landscape. He actively researched native plants throughout his life and became an expert on the subject. In order to continue his life's work, he worked to start a foundation dedicated to the preservation and promotion of native plants of California. Although he first started working toward setting up a foundation in the early 1940s, it did not come into fruition until the late 1950s. He worked on the foundation and other endeavors relating to native plants up until his death. Theodore Payne died May 6, 1963 at 91 years old.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Theodore Payne papers consists of records created or collected by Payne during the course of his life and career. Materials include personal papers, business records, records pertaining to his professional interests and activities, photographs, lantern slides, glass plate negatives, publications on horticulture and gardening, landscaping records, drafts and final publications of Payne's writings and speeches, and herbarium specimens and other artifacts belonging to Payne.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains material from Theodore Payne's personal life. These records include financial records, legal documents, correspondence, photographs, and postcards. Items include a diary belonging to his mother, personal correspondence between his family and friends, photographs and correspondence regarding his 80th birthday, and condolences to his wife, Alice, after Payne's death.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series covers Theodore Payne's professional activities, not directly related to his nursery. Included are Payne's plant research and identification, educational outreach, speeches, writings for articles and books, and Payne's participation in a wide range of clubs and associations in the greater Los Angeles area, Santa Barbara, and Orange County. Materials in this series cover topics such as the history of California horticulture, advocacy in saving native habitats and plants, urban development in the Los Angeles area, and narratives on changing the landscape and the increasing difficulty of finding plants in the wild.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries comprises letters regarding Payne's participation in the preservation of and education about California's native plants. The subseries contains information on speeches and educational programs that Payne conducted. There is also a large amount of material concerning California's changing landscape and the identification of plant species as well as their history. There are many letters from botanists and horticulturalists at universities, botanical gardens, state and federal departments, and museums asking Payne for information on California plants. There are a few letters of note in this series from California governors, botanist Kate Sessions, suffragist Sarah Bard Field, and a poem from Edna St. Vincent Millay

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries includes drafts for Theodore Payne's books: Life on the Modjeska Ranch; Adventures Among the Southern California Plants; and Brief History of a Life in Horticulture. There are also writings promoting wildflowers, native plants, eucalyptus, and other specialty plants; and a few drafts and note cards for speeches on the same topics. Most of the writing and speech topics relate to the value of wildflowers and native plants, and how to use them in gardens and landscapes.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries consists of material from the various Southern California clubs and associations Payne participated in, including the Arboricultural Association, the Audubon Society, Rancho Santa Ana Botanic Garden, Southern California Academy of Sciences, and the Theodore Payne Foundation. His work in these groups ranged from advocacy against destruction of native landscapes, educational outreach, promoting native plants in gardens, and educational programs. Materials include association publications, correspondence, speech drafts, meeting notes, and reports. There are also significant materials dealing with environmental preservation issues for Griffith Park and Hancock Park.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Materials in this subseries cover Payne's activities as a consultant for individuals, government offices, universities, and local associations. Payne consulted on topics such as landscaping, native plant education, and other horticultural topics. Significant topics are a survey on the Mediterranean fruit fly, the 1932 Olympic Beautification Project, and Rancho Santa Ana Botanic Garden.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries is comprised of materials created by Payne, as he researched various topics in horticulture and botany. Materials include correspondence on specific topics, notes, unpublished writings, and experiment records. There are research notes on plant climates and habitats, specimen identification, planting instructions, lists and categories of plants, and an essay titled, "Historical Horticultural Notes."

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains material published or created by people other than Theodore Payne. Materials include gardening magazines, nursery catalogs, informational pamphlets, scientific publications, travel brochures, and publications from associations and conferences. Topics include eucalyptus, California native plants, agriculture, and gardening. Items include state and national park publications, Western Shade Tree publications, several issues of Flora and Sylva (1904, 1905), Sylva of California (1910), several issues of Gardener's Chronicle (1897â€“1927), and several issues of Rural Californian. Boxes 16-18 hold a card index of plant related books listed in alphabetical order by author.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries includes awards and recognitions Payne received during his lifetime. There is also a folder containing written lists of honors and awards received by Payne.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains nursery and plant-related books, pamphlets, and bulletins published from 1901-1979. Box 32 includes Pacific Garden and Eucalypts of Australia.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series comprises records created by Payne's nursery for all activities.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains records that support the administrative functions of the Theodore Payne Nursery. Materials include licenses and permits, leases, patents and copyrights, information for investors, and a plot plans for the Theodore Payne Nursery at 2969 Los Feliz Boulevard.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries includes mail orders and other communications from prominent botanical gardens and nurseries from the East Coast, England, France, Holland, South Africa, Japan, Australia, and Latin America. It also provides information about the organizations and causes to which Theodore Payne donated seeds and plants. Also included is correspondence about planting instructions, customer interactions, and general horticulture advice. There are also four hardbound volumes of correspondence.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains inventories, invoices, shipping receipts, banking information, tax records, ledgers, price lists, and receipts. All records pertaining to Theodore Payne's bankruptcy have been placed in a discrete series. Payne appears to have gathered these documents together, most likely for reference in his prolonged struggle. Materials in this series include letters of recommendation, information for investors, financial documents, bank records, court documents, and letters and articles written by Payne. Documents date from around 1930 to 1940.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains material relating to the promotion and marketing of the Theodore Payne Nursery. Other materials include seed packets and other packaging; mailing and contact lists; advertisements, informational pamphlets, and flyers; and information on flower shows in which Payne participated.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains the Theodore Payne Nursery catalogs filed in chronological order: Box 44: 1904-1916; Box 45:1917-1930; Box 46: 1931-1956 and two undated catalogs.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains propagation journals, planting plans for the nursery, seed mix recipes, notes on stock, seed collecting data, herbarium of 18 samples, and notes on the plant species, Lupinus Paynei.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains two books labeled Nursery Sales and Seed Sales from 1955-1959.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains material pertaining to the design, construction, and planting of landscape projects. Materials include price quotes, records of labor, planning notes, reports, and drawn plans. Also included are the landscaping plans for the Pratt House by Greene and Greene and the Mosk House by Richard Neutra. Box 53 includes Landscape Project Invoices, Miscellaneous Projects A-Z and named projects Ainley - Burhaus. Box 54 includes projects California Institute of Technology - Fantou. Box 55 includes projects Farnham - Loomis. Box 56 includes projects Los Angeles, City of - Williams, Wayne.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of three-dimensional objects such as wallets, a camera, seed and wood samples, a trophy, and some personal items belonging to Theodore Payne.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series is comprised of photographs, slides, and film. Formats include lantern slides, glass plate negatives, and 8mm film reels.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Large portions of the photographs are of plant specimens used for nursery catalogs or for plant identification. Other photographs cover a wide range of subjects including a portrait of Theodore Payne and views of the street entrance of the Payne Nursery and the Los Angeles area in the early 20th century.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains glass plate negatives, box 72; photographic slides, box 73; and color glass plates, boxes 75 and 76. The plates in box 76 are identified as W. Scott Lewis and numbered.
